00:02:28.299 --> 00:02:34.019
Yeah, yeah, it was a good lunch. I don't quite
know what that says about how much time y'all

00:02:34.019 --> 00:02:39.840
have on your hands. But um, alright, so I'm
going to uh talk a little bit about my last

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:45.510
book, which is called Bad Mother. Um, and
in particular, one area that I never get to

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:48.340
talk about this cause I never know whether
any body in my audience will really get what

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:52.680
I'm talking about, so it's a pleasure to be
here and I assume you all are going to understand

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:56.980
what I'm, my reference is. So, when I first
got pregnant with my son Zeke, who's my second

00:02:56.980 --> 00:03:02.370
kid, who's 13 years old now, the first thing
I did; absolutely first thing I did even before

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:08.939
I verified that I was pregnant was, I joined
an on-line support group for mothers due in

00:03:08.939 --> 00:03:15.439
the month of June, 1997. Okay, so that was
like, totally dark ages, right, way back in

00:03:15.439 --> 00:03:21.019
1997. There were no Yahoo groups, there were
no Google groups, nobody had even heard of

00:03:21.019 --> 00:03:27.010
you guys. Those were the days when we were
using things like Alta Vista and Ask Jeeves

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:34.199
no less. For navigation through the ether
I don't know how, how many of you live in

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:37.430
the East Bay but there was an Ask Jeeves billboard
up for just forever, long after it became

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:43.790
sort of the poignant reminder of the early
days of the internet. But that's when I joined

00:03:43.790 --> 00:03:51.150
this first email group. Um, there wasn't even
a web yet. People were just, people who knew

00:03:51.150 --> 00:03:53.879
what the web was were starting to talk about
it, but to everybody else, we just called

00:03:53.879 --> 00:04:01.450
it the internet. Um, and there certainly were
not 500 million blogs with information about,

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:09.019
you know, the genesis of toenail fungus, whether
Matt Smith can really step into David Tennant's

00:04:09.019 --> 00:04:11.659
shoes, anybody? [applause] Thank you.

00:04:11.659 --> 00:04:14.010
[female voice]: He can't.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:21.850
Ayelet: No, I know, it's a heartbreak. Those
were more innocent times before the proliferation

00:04:21.850 --> 00:04:27.710
of Mommy blogs and online parenting magazines.
Andy Lamont was still over at Mothers Who

00:04:27.710 --> 00:04:32.630
Think and Salon. Do you remember those long-ago
days when she was blogging about her baby

00:04:32.630 --> 00:04:37.940
Sam; and it was before she'd even published
any of those books that made her such a superstar

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:43.200
and um, just to give you an idea how long
ago that was, Sam, the baby, she was writing

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:48.470
articles about because they were not blog
posts then, just had his own kid. Okay, so

00:04:48.470 --> 00:04:52.780
that's how long ago we're talking about. Now
I had a group of friends at the time, who

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:59.150
were using email regularly and this was not
common, I mean sure, all of you probably were,

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:04.600
but this was not really common. They didn't
use it as much as I did maybe because they

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:11.490
had yet to quit their time-consuming and intellectually-satisfying
jobs for the more mundane pleasures of killing

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:16.639
time while the baby naps, but there were 13
of us some of us knew each other from Wesleyan

00:05:16.639 --> 00:05:21.161
University some had gone to school at Columbia
Journalism School. It was this little, we

00:05:21.161 --> 00:05:26.240
had, I had my Junebug list and I had this
little internet group of women who [skips]

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:35.110
most of the group of friends, I don't know
if I should tell you the name of that group,

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:39.700
what we called ourselves. But suffice it to
say that this was a time when Cyber still

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:48.570
had kind of a cache about it and um, the literary
genre of Chick Lit had not taken over the

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:52.410
front tables of bookstores, so if you put
that together you can see what horrible name

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:53.960
we came up for our little group.

00:05:53.960 --> 00:06:01.810
Um, my, on all my buddies and I were very
regular emailers. Sometime, each of them shot

00:06:01.810 --> 00:06:09.650
off as many as, wait for it, 10 to 20 emails
per day. But, if you're a fast reader and

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:15.650
you suffer from graphomania as I can do, then
13 correspondents just is not enough no matter

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:20.200
how prolific they are. And, I can email with
those women, but we can talk about things

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:27.210
like whether, you know I don't know what my
baby had done to turn her shit that exact

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:34.480
shade of Easter Egg Blue, [Laughter] I know,
right? I don't know, still to this day. It

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:41.740
happened periodically, and no one has ever
understood the genesis of it. But I wanted,

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:46.301
what I wanted, was companionship with women
who were going through exactly the same thing

00:06:46.301 --> 00:06:50.400
at exactly the same moment. I wanted the,
I wanted to be around a bunch of mothers whose

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:56.250
babies were going to be born in the same month.
So I joined towards, like I said before I

00:06:56.250 --> 00:07:01.540
had even gotten confirmation that I was pregnant,
and this was the listserv expectant mothers

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:06.870
due in June of about 50 women in at the time
that I joined. Over the course of the next,

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:11.790
of that first trimester it fluctuated in size
increasing as more people discovered they're

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:15.952
pregnant or discovered the listserv ebbing
at the eight week mark which, you all probably

00:07:15.952 --> 00:07:21.860
know why, some people found out they weren't
pregnant anymore, that first ultrasound.

00:07:21.860 --> 00:07:27.661
There were people from all over the English-speaking
world, most of us were American. They were

00:07:27.661 --> 00:07:33.290
obviously women of all economic classes, single
mothers on welfare, wives of investment bankers,

00:07:33.290 --> 00:07:38.370
waitresses, pediatric nurses, neurosurgeons,
these were some of the few that I remember.

00:07:38.370 --> 00:07:43.740
There was almost no racial diversity but with
a few exceptions, all women were white but

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:47.650
in other ways it was a pretty diverse group
of people, right? There was, pretty much anybody

00:07:47.650 --> 00:07:55.680
who had a computer who got knocked up in the
September or October [laughter] of 1996. And

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:59.680
as you, I'm not telling you guys anything
you don't I know many of you were also back

00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:04.760
in those early days member of those listservs
or are now. It was, for me it these were all

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:10.830
women that I was not likely to come across
during my day-to-day life. At that point,

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:17.150
my life had kind of constricted to this tiny
universe of playgrounds and Gymboree classes

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:24.440
in West Los Angeles. [INAUDIBLE] there was
one woman whose husband left her second month

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:30.080
of her fifth pregnancy leaving her to raise
all five of her kids without any financial

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:35.719
or emotional assistance. That was pretty amazing.
There was a pediatric oncologist who left

00:08:35.719 --> 00:08:40.709
her practice when she got pregnant with her,
and here's what we call them, Junebugs, got

00:08:40.709 --> 00:08:48.430
pregnant with her Junebug and became the first
and surely the most overqualified lesbian

00:08:48.430 --> 00:08:55.569
Brownie Troop leader in Hercules, California.
There was an internet entrepreneur supporting

00:08:55.569 --> 00:09:00.700
her agoraphobic DH, I assume you all understand
the reference who, by the time her husband

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:06.819
or her Junebug was born was neither a D nor
an H. And then there was my personal favorite,

00:09:06.819 --> 00:09:12.420
the reason I stayed with the group I'm sure
is the poly-amorous frequent poster who just

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:19.889
kind of never understood why her partner's
other partner was not as excited about the

00:09:19.889 --> 00:09:26.149
pregnancy as she was. [Laughter] So, needless
to say, I loved communicating with these total

00:09:26.149 --> 00:09:29.949
strangers, even as they occasionally drove
me nuts. Come on in and sit down. Because

00:09:29.949 --> 00:09:34.990
they were whining about hemorrhoids and breast
tenderness, but I was whining about hemorrhoids

00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:38.740
and breast tenderness. And so, it was just
this wonderful way to go online and whine

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:43.440
about hemorrhoids and breast tenderness with
people who cared about my hemorrhoids and

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:50.910
my breast tenderness. Everybody else in my
life kind of rebelled at this soul crushing

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:59.459
self-absorption that seems to come over me
whenever I'm pregnant or alive, but I was

00:09:59.459 --> 00:10:06.070
rapt. I was rapt by all of these conversations.
And, um you know, that period of pregnancy

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:10.940
I don't think I'm unique in feeling like it's
a time of your life where you are completely

00:10:10.940 --> 00:10:16.540
absorbed with navel gazing obvious, for obvious
reasons, because your navel is becoming ever

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:20.490
more prominent. But you know you spend all
your time that you're not working considering

00:10:20.490 --> 00:10:23.850
being pregnant and rubbing cocoa butter all
over your belly so it's nice to be with other

00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:24.850
people who are doing the same thing.

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:30.779
So this was a really sweet and supportive
group. Right? We took up a collection for

00:10:30.779 --> 00:10:36.869
that mother of five. We bought her car seats
and strollers and everything she needed to

00:10:36.869 --> 00:10:42.830
have that baby. Whenever anybody shared bad
news, we were always sympathetic. Um, at that,

00:10:42.830 --> 00:10:48.689
those early days, we had yet, most of us to
come across an internet troll. There were,

00:10:48.689 --> 00:10:54.699
I think there were just fewer of them back
then. But even in those halcyon early internet

00:10:54.699 --> 00:10:59.319
days, we got into flame wars. They were over
the usual subjects and usually anybody who

00:10:59.319 --> 00:11:04.360
had spent even an hour on the Mommy websites
knows what they're like; breast feeding versus

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:09.579
bottle feeding, cloth diapers versus disposable,
the safety of anal sex during pregnancy [laughter]

00:11:09.579 --> 00:11:14.890
okay that was the poly-amorous mom, although
I'm willing to bet there were some people

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:21.300
who were kind of glad for the sharing of information
on that particular subject. I tried very hard

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:28.449
not to start flame wars myself, but I do have
to admit that I was fairly often the first

00:11:28.449 --> 00:11:34.560
to launch a spirited defense of any member
who I thought was being unjustly attacked.

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:38.759
But, like I said, this group never generated
into true hideousness, because, and here's

00:11:38.759 --> 00:11:46.350
the most important part, we were not anonymous.
We all used our real names, and I'm sure that

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:51.220
it's possible that there was some Julie or
Joanne who was really a troll named Phillip

00:11:51.220 --> 00:11:57.709
wearing crusty boxer shorts and a coffee spattered
wife beater hunched over his laptop in a cockroach-infested

00:11:57.709 --> 00:12:03.540
studio apartment in Van Nuys getting off on
pretending to be a 28-year-old Mormon woman

00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:09.600
from Salt Lake expecting her third baby on
June 14th, it didn't seem likely. And even

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:14.470
if there was such a troll, that Phillip did
such a good job, you know [laughter] of supporting

00:12:14.470 --> 00:12:19.179
us and talking about his baby that it just
didn't really matter whether he was real or

00:12:19.179 --> 00:12:24.769
not. We believed it and we needed it. And
we got what we were looking for, we got reassurance

00:12:24.769 --> 00:12:31.680
that we were normal, we got someone to listen
to us, we were made to feel, by one another,

00:12:31.680 --> 00:12:38.319
that we were good enough. We were all going
to be good mothers, right? Then, after that

00:12:38.319 --> 00:12:46.029
initial glory days of early internet, I expanded
my web communities beyond this fairly personal

00:12:46.029 --> 00:12:53.399
list and of course the level of discourse
deteriorated. [INAUDIBLE] sense of well being.

00:12:53.399 --> 00:13:06.309
[INAUDIBLE] a show of hands. That's it? [INAUDIBLE]
You people must be so busy.

00:13:06.309 --> 00:13:17.760
[laughter]. You know they still give great
information, you know you can buy discount

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:25.360
Robeez, those little slippers, but they do
seem to generate all the time and at an ever

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:31.439
increasing into full pitch hysterical battles,
the subtext of which not only do you and I

00:13:31.439 --> 00:13:39.920
don't agree with each other but your opinion
[INAUDIBLE] and fundamental idiocy makes you

